    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE / 2000 4000 and 8000 MODELS BUILT OCTOBER 1, 1998 AND AFTER -
        ALLISON 2000 SERIES&#8482; (LCT) TRANSMISSION ELECTRONIC CONTROLS - DESCRIPTION - THE NEUTRAL START REVERSE
        SIGNAL SWITCH (NSBU)
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="1">
        <title>THE NEUTRAL START REVERSE SIGNAL SWITCH (NSBU)</title>
        <para>The NSBU (See
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0824704">Figure 4</hotlnk>) is installed on the transmission housing and detects the
            angular position of the shift selector shaft. Output from the NSBU is used to inform the TCM of the selected
            gear and also functions as the neutral safety switch and back-up light switch. The TCM will sense a switch
            or wire failure on circuits from the NSBU.
        </para>
        <figure id="f0824704" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg08/g0824704.png" type="png" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" resolution="200"/>
            <caption>THE NEUTRAL START REVERSE SIGNAL SWITCH (COMMONLY CALLED NSBU)</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. 7 WAY CONNECTOR (3026)</callout1>
                <callout1>2. 4 WAY CONNECTOR (3025)</callout1>
                <callout1>3. SHIFT SELECTOR SHAFT</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
